Key Unity-specific content notes

ScriptableObjects:
Use ScriptableObject types for MissionConfig, FactionConfig, GadgetConfig, WeaponConfig, SkinConfig to enable easy in-editor tweaking and data-driven design.
Example: public class MissionConfig : ScriptableObject { public string id; public string name; public Environment environment; public List<Objective> objectives; public int difficulty; public int moralityImpact; public BranchingRules branchingRules; }
Data-driven config:
MissionConfig.json and other JSON files can be parsed at startup to populate in-memory data or used as backup data; ScriptableObjects can be generated from these at import time or via editor tooling.
Scenes and prefabs:
Provide a SandboxTest scene to rapidly iterate weapon/gadget physics.
MissionHub for mission selection and branching UI.
Input:
Map PS/PC controls in a simple InputManager or using Unity's new Input System for cross-platform mapping.
Build:
Target PC, PS5/PS4 if desired, with platform-specific input prompts in UI.
Core gameplay systems (Unity-oriented)

Gadgets and weapons
Drones: reconnaissance, hacking modules, turret-like support
Energy shields: deployable shield walls with cooldown and regeneration
Cloaks: cloak duration, cooldown, and detection risk
Hacking: device interactions, gate controls, turret disablement
Weapons: modular carbine with upgrade paths (ammo types, scopes, stability)
Perks/Mods: cooldown reductions, drone battery efficiency, movement modifiers
Solo progression
Early, mid, late-game loadouts
Mission pacing aligned to branching outcomes
Coop progression
Roles: Lead Scout, Anchor, Ghost, Tech Specialist
Shared cooldowns and synergy bonuses
Coordinated breaches, hacks, and retreats
Morality and faction branching
GlobalMorality: -100 to +100
= 50: Dawn Accord paths

< 0: Echo Collapse paths
0–49: Grey Protocol
FactionTrust: 0–100 per faction; unlock buffs or side quests at higher trust
